content.text:
The issue was a `NullPointerException` occurring in `EditPostRepository.getDateCreated`. This happened because `PublishSettingsViewModel.start` called `getCurrentPublishDateAsCalendar`, which in turn accessed `postRepository.dateCreated`. The `EditPostRepository` implementation accesses `post!!.dateCreated` without checking if `post` is non-null. When the repository was in a state where no post was loaded (e.g., during initialization or after clearing), this access resulted in a crash.

I fixed the issue by modifying `PublishSettingsViewModel.getCurrentPublishDateAsCalendar` to check if the repository has a loaded post before attempting to access the `dateCreated` property. I used `postRepository.getPost() != null` for this check, which ensures safety in production (where `getPost()` returns the internal `post` object) and maintains compatibility with existing unit tests (where `getPost()` is mocked but `hasPost()` might not be).

**Relevant changes:**

1.  Modified `WordPress/src/main/java/org/wordpress/android/ui/posts/PublishSettingsViewModel.kt`:
    *   Updated `getCurrentPublishDateAsCalendar` to verify `postRepository.getPost() != null` before accessing `postRepository.dateCreated`.

This change prevents the `NullPointerException` by ensuring we only access post properties when a valid post object exists in the repository, falling back to the current calendar time otherwise.

```kotlin
    private fun getCurrentPublishDateAsCalendar(postRepository: EditPostRepository): Calendar {
        val calendar = localeManagerWrapper.getCurrentCalendar()
        if (postRepository.getPost() != null) {
            val dateCreated = postRepository.dateCreated
            // Set the currently selected time if available
            if (!TextUtils.isEmpty(dateCreated)) {
                calendar.time = DateTimeUtils.dateFromIso8601(dateCreated)
                calendar.timeZone = localeManagerWrapper.getTimeZone()
            }
        }
        return calendar
    }
```

